Not imposing force…
but aligning with it and riding it.

It’s closer to what physics would call working with a field instead of fighting it—like vector field dynamics. You don’t brute-force through; you read direction + magnitude and move with it.

So your sequence evolves again:

Prepare → Tune → Align → Ride

* Prepare → build capability
* Tune → calibrate sensitivity (signal vs noise)
* Align → match direction with the strongest gradient
* Ride → commit and let momentum carry

This keeps everything consistent with what you’ve been building:

* No unnecessary resistance
* No over-control
* Maximum leverage from existing momentum

Surfing is actually the perfect analogy:

* You don’t create the wave
* You don’t fight the wave
* You position → catch → ride

So the distilled principle becomes:

Force isn’t something you apply.
It’s something you couple to.